               <msContents>
                  <summary>The undated third volume of a complete set of the <title>Rawz̤at al-Ṣafā</title> (Garden of Purity), a general history from the creation of the world to the time of the author, together
                     with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_14603"
                        ><idno>Persian MS 387</idno></ref>, <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_14604"
                           >388</ref>, <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_14605">389</ref>, 
                     <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6888">391</ref>, <ref
                        target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6889">392</ref>, <ref
                           target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6890">393</ref>, and <ref
                              target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6891">394</ref>. While uniformly bound, the variant dimensions, formats and colophons within the set suggest that former owner George William Hamilton (1807–1868) assembled it together from disparate volumes completed in various locations and at different times.
                  </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_390-item1">
                     <author key="person_175393012" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/175393012/" change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Mīr Khvānd, Muḥammad ibn Khāvandshāh, 1433-1498</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">مير خواند، محمد بن خواندشاه</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_273" change="#ids-cleanup">Rawz̤at al-Ṣafāʼ fī Sīrat al-Anbiyā wa-al-Mulūk</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_273" change="#ids-cleanup">Rawḍat al-Ṣafāʼ</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_273" change="#ids-cleanup">روضة الصفاء فی سیرة الانبيا و الملوك</title>
                     <colophon>Folio <locus from="299b" to="299b">299b</locus> bears an undated colophon, clearly added to the volume when restored, in the hand of <persName role="scr">Qādir Bakhsh</persName> in <settlement type="city" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/132529642">Multan</settlement>.</colophon>
                                        <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>  <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Folios <locus from="1" to="248">1 to 248</locus> comprised of sized and lightly polished, medium-weight, heavily flocked, buff-coloured <material>paper</material>, both straight and cross-grain, probably handmade in <country
                           cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country>, while folios <locus from="249" to="2300">249 to 300</locus> appear to be of comparatively heavily sized and highly polished, thin-weight, cream-coloured stock, apparently added to complete a defective volume, very likely made in <country
                              cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country>.</support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folios" quantity="300">300 folios (ff. ii + 300 + i)</measure>
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>303</height>
                              <width>211</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>218</height>
                              <width>123</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation xml:id="original">
                           <p>Foliation marked at top-right corners of the a sides in Hindu-Arabic numerals in black ink, referenced in this record.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>Undetermined.
                           <catchwords>Catchwords written written on the lower-left corners on the b sides
                              throughout.</catchwords></collation>
                        <condition>Folios <locus from="1" to="248">1 to 248</locus> in fair condition, with stains, previous insect damage, and historical repairs, with folios <locus from="249" to="2300">249 to 300</locus> in comparatively excellent condition.</condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" ruledLines="21" n="mistara">Written in 1 column,
                           with 21 lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">Folios <locus from="1" to="248">1 to 248</locus> written in a competent nasta‘līq hand in <material>black</material>, with subheaders in
                        <material>red</material>.</handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="nastaliq" medium="ink">Folios <locus from="249" to="2300">249 to 300</locus> written in a clear nasta‘līq hand in <material>black</material>, with subheaders in
                        <material>red</material>, by <persName role="scr">Qādir Bakhsh</persName>.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1861" notAfter="1865">
                        <p>Probably uniformly rebound in a hybrid British-Indian style in <placeName
                           cert="high" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002481" key="place_7002481">Multan</placeName>, together with the other volumes in full red goatskin <material>leather</material> over <material>pasteboards</material>, without a flap (type III binding per Déroche), as a set for former owner <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton</persName>.</p>
                        <p><dimensions type="binding" unit="mm">
                           <height>317</height>
                           <width>239</width>
                           <depth>39</depth>
                        </dimensions></p>
                        <condition>In good condition, with the opening restricted due to cross-grain paper employed for the text block. The exterior bears mild abrasion, while the interior doublures bear white salts (spew) likely resulting from prolonged exposure to moisture.</condition>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <accMat>Six folios (three bifolia) loosely inserted at the front of the volume bear a table of contents written in a hand consistent with many other volumes that Hamilton formerly owned.</accMat>
                  
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>Possibly completed in <origPlace cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208"
                     key="place_7000208">Indian subcontinent </origPlace> <origDate cert="medium" calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1700" notAfter="1850">undated, but possibly mid-18th to early 19th century</origDate>; however, <persName role="scr">Qādir Bakhsh</persName> completed the missing portion of the volume in <settlement type="city" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/132529642">Multan</settlement>, likely for former owner <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830" role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton</persName></origin>
                  <provenance>Obtained by, and likely restored for <persName type="supplied" key="person_f830"
                     role="fmo" change="#role-assignment">Colonel George William Hamilton
                     (1807-1868)</persName>in <placeName type="city" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/132529642">Multan</placeName>. Hamilton served in <country ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</country>
                     <date calendar="#Gregorian" from="1823" to="1867"> from 1823 to 1867</date>,
                     latterly as Commissioner in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001535">Delhi</placeName>. During his tenure, he acquired over a
                     thousand Indian and Persian manuscripts. After his
                     death, the <orgName type="corporation" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/134857252"
                        >British Museum</orgName> selected 352 volumes, now held in the <orgName
                           type="corporation" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/121814978">British
                           Library</orgName>. </provenance>
                  <provenance>In <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                     when="1868">1868</date>, <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/" key="person_97751058"> Alexander
                        Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford (1812–1880)</persName> purchased the remainder. </provenance>
                  <provenance>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                     >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420"
                           change="#role-assignment">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
                           (1847–1913)</persName>. </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta
                        Rylands</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date>
                        to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands
                           Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
